    "instruction": "Using metric.csv only, perform the following steps and return a compact aggregate result (do not print full time series):\n1) For each unique (cmdb_id, kpi_name) pair present in metric.csv, compute the global P95 value across the full available series for that pair. Also compute the global P50 (median) for reference. Keep these as a table in the kernel.\n2) Filter metric.csv to only rows whose timestamp falls within the incident window 2024-01-19 04:40:34 UTC to 2024-01-19 05:10:34 UTC (inclusive). Note: timestamps are in seconds and should be parsed to UTC datetimes by the Executor.\n3) For each (cmdb_id, kpi_name) pair, within the incident-window subset, count how many data points exceed the global P95 (for KPIs where larger means worse, e.g., cpu, mem, latency-50, latency-90, diskio, socket, error); for KPIs that represent traffic/throughput where a drop is bad (e.g., workload, success rate) also compute how many points fall below global P05 and below global P15 (if workload exists). Return a compact table of the top 20 (cmdb_id, kpi_name) pairs ranked by number of anomalous points, with these columns: cmdb_id, kpi_name, anomaly_count, total_points_in_window, earliest_anomalous_timestamp (UTC), max_value_in_window, global_P95, global_P50. If no anomaly according to P95 is found, also include pairs that breach P90 (indicate which threshold used). Limit returned rows to at most 20.\nReturn only the aggregate table described and a short note if any (cmdb_id,kpi) had zero points in-window (list up to 10 such pairs)."
